34    /**
35    * Controls the printing and parsing of a datetime to and from a string.
36    * <p>
37    * This class is the main API for printing and parsing used by most applications.
38    * Instances of this class are created via one of three factory classes:
39    * <ul>
40    * <li>{@link DateTimeFormat} - formats by pattern and style</li>
41    * <li>{@link ISODateTimeFormat} - ISO8601 formats</li>
42    * <li>{@link DateTimeFormatterBuilder} - complex formats created via method calls</li>
43    * </ul>
44    * <p>
45    * An instance of this class holds a reference internally to one printer and
46    * one parser. It is possible that one of these may be null, in which case the
47    * formatter cannot print/parse. This can be checked via the {@link #isPrinter()}
48    * and {@link #isParser()} methods.
49    * <p>
50    * The underlying printer/parser can be altered to behave exactly as required
51    * by using one of the decorator modifiers:
52    * <ul>
53    * <li>{@link #withLocale(Locale)} - returns a new formatter that uses the specified locale</li>
54    * <li>{@link #withZone(DateTimeZone)} - returns a new formatter that uses the specified time zone</li>
55    * <li>{@link #withChronology(Chronology)} - returns a new formatter that uses the specified chronology</li>
56    * <li>{@link #withOffsetParsed()} - returns a new formatter that returns the parsed time zone offset</li>
57    * <li>{@link #withPivotYear(int)} - returns a new formatter with the specified pivot year</li>
58    * <li>{@link #withDefaultYear(int)} - returns a new formatter with the specified default year</li>
59    * </ul>
60    * Each of these returns a new formatter (instances of this class are immutable).
61    * <p>
62    * The main methods of the class are the <code>printXxx</code> and
63    * <code>parseXxx</code> methods. These are used as follows:
64    * <pre>
65    * // print using the defaults (default locale, chronology/zone of the datetime)
66    * String dateStr = formatter.print(dt);
67    * // print using the French locale
68    * String dateStr = formatter.withLocale(Locale.FRENCH).print(dt);
69    * // print using the UTC zone
70    * String dateStr = formatter.withZone(DateTimeZone.UTC).print(dt);
71    *
72    * // parse using the Paris zone
73    * DateTime date = formatter.withZone(DateTimeZone.forID("Europe/Paris")).parseDateTime(str);
74    * </pre>
75    * <p>
76    * Parsing builds up the resultant instant by 'setting' the value of each parsed field
77    * from largest to smallest onto an initial instant, typically 1970-01-01T00:00Z.
78    * This design means that day-of-month is set before day-of-week.
79    * As such, if both the day-of-month and day-of-week are parsed, and the day-of-week
80    * is incorrect, then the day-of-week overrides the day-of-month.
81    * <p>
82    * This has a side effect if the input is not consistent.
83    *
84    * @author Brian S O'Neill
85    * @author Stephen Colebourne
86    * @author Fredrik Borgh
87    * @since 1.0
88    */

393    /**
394    * Returns a new formatter that will use the specified pivot year for two
395    * digit year parsing in preference to that stored in the parser.
396    * <p>
397    * This setting is useful for changing the pivot year of formats built
398    * using a pattern - {@link DateTimeFormat#forPattern(String)}.
399    * <p>
400    * When parsing, this pivot year is used. Null means no-override.
401    * There is no effect when printing.
402    * <p>
403    * The pivot year enables a two digit year to be converted to a four
404    * digit year. The pivot represents the year in the middle of the
405    * supported range of years. Thus the full range of years that will
406    * be built is <code>(pivot - 50) .. (pivot + 49)</code>.
407    *
408    * <pre>
409    * pivot supported range 00 is 20 is 40 is 60 is 80 is
410    * ---------------------------------------------------------------
411    * 1950 1900..1999 1900 1920 1940 1960 1980
412    * 1975 1925..2024 2000 2020 1940 1960 1980
413    * 2000 1950..2049 2000 2020 2040 1960 1980
414    * 2025 1975..2074 2000 2020 2040 2060 1980
415    * 2050 2000..2099 2000 2020 2040 2060 2080
416    * </pre>
417    *
418    * @param pivotYear the pivot year to use as an override when parsing
419    * @return the new formatter
420    * @since 1.1
421    */
 
100% Uncovered Elements: 0 (5) Complexity: 4 Complexity Density: 1.33

430    /**
431    * Returns a new formatter that will use the specified pivot year for two
432    * digit year parsing in preference to that stored in the parser.
433    * <p>
434    * This setting is useful for changing the pivot year of formats built
435    * using a pattern - {@link DateTimeFormat#forPattern(String)}.
436    * <p>
437    * When parsing, this pivot year is used.
438    * There is no effect when printing.
439    * <p>
440    * The pivot year enables a two digit year to be converted to a four
441    * digit year. The pivot represents the year in the middle of the
442    * supported range of years. Thus the full range of years that will
443    * be built is <code>(pivot - 50) .. (pivot + 49)</code>.
444    *
445    * <pre>
446    * pivot supported range 00 is 20 is 40 is 60 is 80 is
447    * ---------------------------------------------------------------
448    * 1950 1900..1999 1900 1920 1940 1960 1980

774    /**
775    * Parses a datetime from the given text, at the given position, saving the
776    * result into the fields of the given ReadWritableInstant. If the parse
777    * succeeds, the return value is the new text position. Note that the parse
778    * may succeed without fully reading the text and in this case those fields
779    * that were read will be set.
780    * <p>
781    * Only those fields present in the string will be changed in the specified
782    * instant. All other fields will remain unaltered. Thus if the string only
783    * contains a year and a month, then the day and time will be retained from
784    * the input instant. If this is not the behaviour you want, then reset the
785    * fields before calling this method, or use {@link #parseDateTime(String)}
786    * or {@link #parseMutableDateTime(String)}.
787    * <p>
788    * If it fails, the return value is negative, but the instant may still be
789    * modified. To determine the position where the parse failed, apply the
790    * one's complement operator (~) on the return value.
791    * <p>
792    * This parse method ignores the {@link #getDefaultYear() default year} and
793    * parses using the year from the supplied instant based on the chronology
794    * and time-zone of the supplied instant.
